 forced to make do with whatever it could get its hands on. That spirit of improvisation carried the IDF to a decisive victory in the First Arab-Israeli War.Today the same spirit has made the IDF the most powerful military in the Middle East and among the most capable in the world. In The Art of Military Innovation, Edward N. Luttwak and Eitan Shamir trace the roots of this astounding success. What sets the IDF apart, they argue, is its singular organizational structure. From its inception, it has been the world’s only one-service military, encompassing air, naval, and land forces in a single institutional body. This unique structure, coupled with a young officer corps, allows for initiative from below. The result is a nimble organization inclined toward change rather than beholden to tradition.The IDF has fostered some of the most significant advances in military technology of the past seventy years, from the first wartime use of drones to the famed Iron Dome missile defense system, and now the first laser weapon, Iron Beam. Less-heralded innovations in training, logistics, and human resources have been equally important. Sharing rich insights and compelling stories, Luttwak and Shamir reveal just what makes the IDF so agile and effective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary art and sciencezIsraelxAutomation. 0aMilitary art and sciencezIsrael. 0aTechnological innovationszIsrael. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh  aArik Sharon.  aArtzav 19.  aAviam Sela.  aAvrham Arnan.  aGhost.  aMatkal.  aMerkava tank.  aMoshe Dayan.  aNamer APC.  aOperation Moked.  aReactive Armor.  aSubterranean Warfare.  aTal.  aTalpiot program.  aUnit 8200.  aentrepreneurs.  amultirole fighter jet.  areserve army.  awomen.1 aShamir, Eitan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re